(12. You can't always trust a BMC's inventory of the server's hardware) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-06-26T03:26:58Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/tech/BMCDontTrustHardwareInventory) Tj
T*
(Many BMCs will tell you what hardware your server or other system has in it. This is a useful,) Tj
T*
(even valuable function, but you shouldn't necessarily trust what your BMC is saying. We) Tj
T*
(recently had a very vivid demonstration of that, where the BMC of a server confidently reported) Tj
T*
(that the hardware had a number of inexpensive NVMe SSDs, a bunch of \(expensive\) RAM, and a pair) Tj
T*
(of processors, but mysteriously the server wouldn't power on at all. When we opened up the) Tj
T*
(server, we found no NVMe SSDs, no RAM, and especially no processors, which did rather explain) Tj
T*
(the failure to power on. Since the BMC in question offered us the option of downloading the raw) Tj
T*
(SMBIOS information, my best guess is that the BMC gets its hardware inventory by having the) Tj
T*
(main system's BIOS push the SMBIOS blob to it when the BIOS powers on or otherwise goes through) Tj
T*
(a state change. The last time the system was powered on, it presumably had all of those NVMe) Tj
T*
(SSDs, the RAM, and the processors, and now the BMC has that state latched until the next time) Tj
T*
(the system can power up. I was going to say that it made sense from a technical perspective) Tj
T*
(too, but the more I think about it the less I'm completely convinced of that...) Tj
T*
() Tj
